#=GF TP   Domain
#=GF WK   RNA_recognition_motif
#=GF CL   CL0221
#=GF RN   [1]
#=GF RM   8290338
#=GF RT   Analysis of the RNA-recognition motif and RS and RGG domains:
#=GF RT   conservation in metazoan pre-mRNA splicing factors.
#=GF RA   Birney E., Kumar S., Krainer A.R.
#=GF RL   Nucleic Acid Res 1993;21:5803-5816.
#=GF DR   INTERPRO; IPR000504;
#=GF DR   PROSITE; PDOC00030;
#=GF DR   SCOP; 1sxl; sf;
#=GF DR   MIM; 152700;
#=GF DR   MIM; 109090;
#=GF DR   HOMSTRAD; rrm;
#=GF DR   SO; 0000417; polypeptide_domain;
#=GF CC   The RRM motif (a.k.a. RRM, RBD, or RNP domain) is probably
#=GF CC   diagnostic of an RNA binding protein. RRMs are found in a
#=GF CC   variety of RNA binding proteins, including various hnRNP
#=GF CC   proteins, proteins implicated in regulation of alternative
#=GF CC   splicing, and protein components of snRNPs. The motif also
#=GF CC   appears in a few single stranded DNA binding proteins. The RRM
#=GF CC   structure consists of four strands and two helices arranged in
#=GF CC   an alpha/beta sandwich, with a third helix present during RNA
#=GF CC   binding in some cases The C-terminal beta strand (4th strand)
#=GF CC   and final helix are hard to align and have been omitted in the
#=GF CC   SEED alignment The LA proteins (Swiss:P05455) have an N terminal
#=GF CC   rrm which is included in the seed. There is a second region
#=GF CC   towards the C terminus that has some features characteristic of
#=GF CC   a rrm but does not appear to have the important structural core
#=GF CC   of a rrm. The LA proteins (Swiss:P05455) are one of the main
#=GF CC   autoantigens in Systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE), an
#=GF CC   autoimmune disease.
#=GF SQ   68
